  <!-- ═══ SENSITIVITY ANALYSIS ═══ -->
  <h2>Sensitivity Analysis</h2>
  <p>Our base case uses {(growthRatePhase1 * 100).toFixed(0)}% growth and {(discountRate * 100).toFixed(0)}% discount rate. Here's what the intrinsic value looks like under different assumptions.</p>

  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table class="sensitivity-table">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th style="text-align:left">Discount Rate ↓ / Growth →</th>
          {sensitivityGrowth.map(g => (
            <th class={g === growthRatePhase1 ? 'current' : ''}>{(g * 100).toFixed(0)}%</th>
          ))}
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        {sensitivityTable.map(row => (
          <tr>
            <td>{(row.dr * 100).toFixed(0)}%</td>
            {row.values.map((v, i) => (
              <td class={row.dr === discountRate && sensitivityGrowth[i] === growthRatePhase1 ? 'current' : ''}>
                ${v}
              </td>
            ))}
          </tr>
        ))}
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>
  <p>The highlighted cell is our base case. Notice how sensitive the result is to the discount rate.</p>

  <!-- ═══ WHAT THE MODEL DOESN'T CAPTURE ═══ -->
  <h2>Risks & What This Model Misses</h2>

  <h3>Upside risks (our number could be too low)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Streaming Profitability Surge:</strong> If Disney+, Hulu, and ESPN+ achieve Netflix-like margins faster than expected, FCF could easily outpace our 8% estimate.</li>
    <li><strong>Parks Expansion:</strong> Significant capacity additions to domestic and international parks could drive structurally higher cash generation.</li>
    <li><strong>Epic Games Partnership:</strong> Successful monetization of Disney IP within Fortnite and a broader gaming universe presents unmodeled upside.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Downside risks (our number could be too high)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Linear TV Decline:</strong> The secular decline of traditional cable networks (ESPN, ABC, Disney Channel) might accelerate, destroying legacy cash flows faster than streaming can replace them.</li>
    <li><strong>Consumer Weakness:</strong> Theme parks are highly discretionary. An economic downturn could severely impact attendance and per-capita spending.</li>
    <li><strong>Content Flops:</strong> A string of expensive box office misses from Marvel, Star Wars, or Pixar can depress theatrical revenue and weaken consumer products licensing.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <details>
      <summary>Why use DCF for Disney?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">While P/E multiples are common, Disney's earnings have been distorted by streaming investments and restructuring charges. A DCF cuts through accounting noise to focus on actual cash generation, which is the ultimate driver of value.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why is Disney's Net Cash negative?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Disney carries substantial debt, largely stemming from the $71 billion acquisition of 21st Century Fox in 2019 and continued capital investments. This debt load is why enterprise value is significantly higher than equity value.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>How does ESPN transition factor in?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">The launch of flagship direct-to-consumer ESPN is a critical inflection point. Our 8% growth assumption embeds a successful, but costly, transition of sports rights into a streaming-first model.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Is this a buy recommendation?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">No. This is an analytical framework for estimating intrinsic value. Whether to buy depends on your personal risk tolerance, portfolio allocation, time horizon, tax situation, and conviction in the assumptions.</div>
    </details>
  </div>

